,Recommended,322300,14302949,"Posted: 2 February, 2015",all,Rkurnelm,"I never had the pleasure of playing Ultima Online.  But I was fortunate enough to play SWG (both pre and post Combat Update and NGE).  Much of The Repopulation is very reminicant of my days as a TKM (Teras Kasi Master) trying to get to blue glowy (Jedi), with some notable exceptions.  Therefore, the comparrison that the company makes is a very fair one as far as SWG is concerned.The game is highly skill based.  There are your main skills (of which there's around 75) and then there are skills within the skills.  I will use the character I have played with the most (I've tinkered with three) to try to illustrate the point.My main character is primarily a hunter type with some gathering side abilities.  There are several but the ones he specializes in are, mining (minerals and ore extraction from nodes), wood cutting (cutting down trees), and survival (skinning animals and scavenging for water).  There's others but those are the ones I use.  For every mob type there is a set skill pertaining to them.  A common early mob is a Setlang, they are reptilian dog-like creatures.  As you hunt/skin more and more of these creatures you begin to become more and more familiar with them.  So there's your overall skill (say survival) and specific species skill (in this case setlang) the higher they both are the better you do, obviously.  This holds true across the board.   Are you a miner?  What kind of miner are you?  There's a skill for each ore too.  Woods man?  What trees/plants are you good with?On the flipside.  Lets say you go into crafting.  The same thing applies you have your base crafting schools, lets say chemistry, and then you have all of your chemistry recipes.  They have separate skills associated with each one of them (i'm quite the badass water distiller but i can't do acid extraction for crap).Harvesting is interesting in that you have several options.  There's auto harvesting (you can put down extractors over some nodes) and there's manual extraction.  Many nodes under manual extraction come with 2 other options enhancement of the node you're on, and enrichment of the area.  As an area is harvested it looses quality and it shows in the nodes.  The immediate and personal fix is by enhancing the node you're working on but it only works for you.  Enriching the area restores the area's quality not just for you but everyone.The game is in alpha so please expect crashes, bugs and issues. They aren't abundant but they exist, most can be fixed with a soft log.ProsMassive skill systemGreat in game communityVery ambitiousRewarding if you're willing to work for it (those who seek immediate gratification go elsewhere)Decent early teaching methods (nooby training instance)ConsSteep price tag for alpha *redacted con, see edit*Alpha lots of bugs, they're being worked on but it's alphaFuture possibility of microtransactionsSteep learning curve, with many skills ""hidden"" for you to discover on your own, and little direction given beyond the original training instanceAll in all, if they add a twitch based flight aspect I will be at their door screaming ""Shut up and take my money"".  As it sits, for me, it is worth the early investment.  These guys are clearly serious and want the game to work.  That being said I enjoy alphas and betas, and realize many don't.  So if you're one who wants a clean and polished game don't buy in yet.  The game is clean and has some polish, but isn't finished yet.  They are making progress (think an update comes out today or tomorrow actually) but they've still got work to do.  The price tag of 40 bucks for an alpha is a bit steep in my opinion but being that it harkens back to my days in SWG as much as it did I took the plunge, and am glad I did.There's many things that you can do in game that I've not mentioned this is strictly the path of one of my characters, the character is truly yours when you get in.Enjoy-RkEdit: Thanks to WubZero for bringing this to my attention.  There's been a price reduction removing that con.  Game is now 20 bucks as opposed to 40 now makes it a very viable competetor in the current market.They do plan on having twitch based flight once they've smoothed out the majority of the ground game.  So we are at ""Shut up and take my money"" status."
,Recommended,322300,14646321,"Posted: 25 February, 2015",all,Sardoni,"2/25/2015 - In the current iteration I feel the game is still in the core gameplay stage of testing.  If you don't know what that means, probably best to avoid the game until it progresses into a beta stage.  The developers always seem active and open to feedback.  GM staff is usually always available in game if you hit a snag with most issues.  /newbie chat is most times filled with helpful people (so long as you actually paid attention during the tutorial :P).I would caution you to bring your engineering degree along if you plan on delving too deeply into crafting because it is quite literally rocket science.  Most crafts also have strong interdependencies relying on the other crafting fields, so it's not a recommended solo experience.  And why have we gotten the notion that MMOs should be solo experiences in all things?  You can eventually grand master every skill line on one character, but don't put the cart before the horse.  Soft cap is currently 6k per skill line (when you stop gaining abilities) with hard cap being 60k per skill line (with small gain improvement depending on the skill line after 6k).This game is trying to recapture many of the sandbox aspects that have been ignored lately in MMOs.  One of the more important being the social aspects that I feel should exist in all MMOs.  You'll need people for far more in this game then hitting the queue button and waiting for a pve dungeon or pvp map with perfect strangers and then never see them again.  Personally I was excited to see sort of a re-imaging of the Entertainer from SWG providing buffs to people who stop into the pub/cantina (the /tip function is also in this game!).I've also missed my Creature Handler and there's a few different pet style branches here as well.  Animal Handling - tame baby animals in the wild to fight for you/become mounts for you and maintain them with Vet Medicine (or let another vet maintain them for you), Robotics - build your own robot and outfit them with fittings to suit your needs, and Genetic Engineering - take tissue samples and dna samples from various creatures and make your own mad scientst one-shot consumable-on-use clone pets.There are 75 total skill lines at the moment to discuss (as well as hidden skill lines), so I won't talk in depth about all those, but I encourage to check out the official site and wiki to learn more.All in all, this game has a solid foundation to be a decent sandbox which the industry is severly lacking at the moment.  If that is a niche you miss or want to delve deeper into; consider backing.  If you'd like to play a more optimized game... continue to wait until this game moves into beta phase (still a few months out from time of posting)."
76561198012073812,Recommended,322300,13979678,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,macidy,"Initially It was fun and frustrating at the same time...then for a few days it seemed to grind on and on and I didn't see much developing with my charicter...(Because like many I didn't read any of the guides and tried to jump in without a clue.) After I read one of the guides...well...It honestly changed the whole game for me and am now making some really decent headway in charicter developement. It is a little rough on load times and still crashes once or twice every couple of hours, but hey...Its Alpha. It was advertised as such so it has to be expected. Honestly though it preforms better than many games I've tried that were full releases. There is ALOT to do, learn and try in this game. It can be a casual game but it's hard to put it down sometimes even when i'm getting stomped. The crafting system is pretty advanced and it has a new skill system similar to that of EVE online. (Skill books.) plus if you buy the weapon skills you get a free gun, grenade or Sword, ax etc. apropriate to the skill learned. (I.e. you leard automatic weapons you get an assault rifle.) One of my two favorite weapons in game so far are the sniper rifle and flame thrower. (You can also add fittings to the weapons and armor to boost certin atributes.) ....and they have pets! Who doesn't want virtual pets...and no virtual Poo to clean up. They have a limited amount of vehicles that I suggest buying for other players rather than NPCs as the quality, availability, and prices are much better...I bought a light mech...It has a gun...I shoot stuff.It's a keeper."
76561197982916996,Recommended,322300,16300986,"Posted: 10 June, 2015",all,samhain323,"1st Impressions review.I love it so far. You can tell where the team's inspiration came from. It reminds me of the early days of SWG and seems to have the best parts of that game, Anarchy Online, UO, Vanguard, and others.Even in alpha the game is playable and easily worth the $20. I've been waiting for a game like this since they butchered SWG. I even went so far as to try SWG emulators and others. I played Vanguard until it went offline as well.The good: Solid base so far. Combat is pretty fun and you get a choice between RPG (tab target) and FPS style. The mission system is convienient and being refined. The skill trees are diverse and varied. The crafting system is complex (see below). There are numerous ways to progress your character (combat, crafting, harvesting, diplomacy, entertainer etc). These  are completley viable playstyles in and of themselves. And you can technically do them all on the same character (classless, lskill point based progression with no limit on skill points accrued). Pets, tamed, bought, built. Yes, you can go tame baby creatures and raise them, build bots, genetically engineer pets, etc.The bad: I love crafting. I spent at least a solid year on SWG doing that almost exclusively (by hand, no macros). I love the fact they are trying hard to make the crafting (and other professions) viable. That being said, at first glance I think it's a bit too complicated and interdependent at the moment. There are very few (if any) low level recipes that are useful in an of themselves. Interdependence among crafters is forced. Even most low level recipes require components from multiple disciplines. You might as well include harvesting in this as well, as your skill at harvesting affects the quality of raw and refined mats. Unfortunatley it relies on the premise there will be crafters fulfilling all the parts required. A crafter just starting out, who has no money, cannot collect higher grade mats, and/or make high grade end products, will basically be forced to run missions and grind out sub-par items for xp.Keep in mind this is a first impression and solely an opinion. I may very well change my mind after a bit more time.That being said, I see HUGE potential. I think they can streamline it a bit, ease up a little on the interdependence, and tone down the recipe complexity a little. Honestly, even if it doesn't change much, I'd still play and most likely craft. I don't see it attracting many crafters in it's current iteration though.I'll update as the game progresses. This is my first review after years of playing games on Steam. I'm not the guy that generally takes time to write reviews, but I really want this game to succeed. I'm tired of the trash that's being churned out."
