76561197970516144,Recommended,322300,16040820,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,Only Jesus Christ Saves,"This game is Alpha and obviously has a lot of work ahead of it but what impresses me is most of the major features seem to work.  It has the potential to be the game I will call home for the foreseeable future.  Skill based system, player crafting economy, player housing/cities/nations and many other great features.  It all reminds me of UO and SWG (both early era) which are two of my favorite games.  If you have never played a skill based game before try it with an open mind.  No more leveling, what you actually do is what you become good at.First off, the game is very rough around the edges.  It’s Alpha so expect Alpha.  For Alpha however it is very impressive compared to others I’ve backed.  Everything in general works.  It might not be pretty but it works.  My review will just be an example of a single play session as a complete noob:Log in, check my in game e-mail for any quests I’m interested in.  If one looks good I take it, if not I simply ignore them.  I hit the local bar/pub (allows you to enter a resting state that makes entertainment abilities usable) to do some Entertainment activities such as dancing and storytelling (this is the game’s buff system, the more people around using entertainment skills the faster you seem to stack buffs and of different types).Once I get 6 stacks of all the buffs I can that last more than an hour, I head out of town, with my Adult Setlang pet and start murdering stuff with my rifle (gaining rifle skill and animal handing doing so).  I harvest any lumber or metal I can find as well as the corpses of the fallen (gaining survival skill and knowledge of what I kill).  Using my survival skills I upgrade the resources harvested as far I can (quality in materials matters to crafters).I’m working on my personal short term goal of building a speeder bike so I focus on the mats needed to create this (found by access an outside website for crafting, expect plenty of this).  If enough time goes by I also use my survival skill to create a camp in the wild to enter a resting state (same as the bar) and refresh my buffs.  If you have 6 stacks with a minute left, it only takes 1 more stack to refresh all stacks to max duration.I find any baby animals I can tame and do so to raise animal handling.  I also have to craft food for my pets and feed them every hour so they can continue to grow to adulthood.  Eventually I’ll be able to turn them into mounts if I choose depending on the animal.Every fight I gain skill in Stealth, light armor and whatever other skills I use.  If I have to run and heal I gain in healing skill.  What you do is what you become good at, you get the idea.That’s a very basic example of what’s going on and it all works.  The animations are rough, the sounds are not great and not directional, the graphics glitch and the engine lags at times especially around what appear to be server lines but it’s still Alpha.  If the game can get polished up it will be a real gem."
,Recommended,322300,14805312,"Posted: 9 March, 2015",all,Veo,"One of the few games out there with such depth.  I've just completed my second week on this game and have been amazed by the vastness of the world and item (read: crafting) system.  I've never played Ultima Online or Star Wars Galaxies, but other players ingame say that those are the closest comparisons.  I like to think of The Repopulation as a Runescape on steroids with a touch of EVE Online. While I could talk about various aspects of the game, I'm going to focus on crafting which seems to be the strongest point in the game currently.Pros - CraftingThere's a highly complex crafting tree for making things like weapons and armor, vehicles, consumables etc.  I specialize in Armor Fittings, which enhance the stats of your armor.  Unlike most MMOs out there, the armor and weapons themselves don't matter as much as the fittings which you insert into them.  In order to craft Armor Fittings I rely on other players to harvest ore, wood and plants which I then turn in to refined metal bars, firewood and chemicals to craft the components that I will eventually need to make a single fitting.  If no one is gathering Calibrite Ore, and the auction house is empty, then I must go out and gather some myself.  Armor Fittings are one recipe of the larger Armor Crafting discipline, which is itself one of several hundred skill paths players can choose from.  The interesting thing is knowing that you rely on other players on your server to gather materials that you can't gather, and to craft items you can't craft yourself.  While you can theoretically DIY, it takes significantly longer than bartering and buying/selling to and from other players.  Plus, advanced items require dozens of ingredients to come together.Cons - CraftingThe system can be daunting to players who are used to very simple crafting systems like World of Warcraft and other theme park MMOs.  In a theme park MMO you would mine ore, refine it into bars, then use that to create items.  On The Repopulation each ore gives different properties to a finished product (armor penetration, damage, resistance, movement speed, critical hit).  Ores also come in varying grades with a letter prefix A-F and an integer suffix 0-9 which can only be harvested by those with high skill in the corresponding ability.  So to make a very good quality Armor Fitting I would need to hire a Master Miner, and a Master Ore Refiner just to ensure that the metal bars I have are the best possible.  I would also need a Master Forager to gather plants, and a Master Chemist to synthesize the compounds I need.  I could do it all myself, but training 4 skills to such a high level would take months to attain.  Recipes are highly complex, and you will find yourself opening your web browser to check on agents, and sub-ingredients to make those agents quite often during crafting.  Once you do get the hang of it, though, it gets much easier and manageable.Cons- OtherThe graphics leave something to be desired.  The engine seems old, so the models ingame from players to NPCs to the environment are lower quality than most people are used to in 2015.  As an alpha game there are some bugs and glitches that still need to be ironed out.  You can phase through objects when zoning between areas, and the combat seems clunky rather than fluid.  With a still new player base, everyone's still in that learning process so it gets frustrating at times when trying to find others to help you build cities or craft items that you need.  The game is not easy to play and requires some thinking.  After playing the game for two weeks it feels like I took college courses in Chemistry, Geology, Mechanical Engineering.  If you're looking to just zone out, then the crafting system isn't for you.  But the combat and doing missions is still very viable for someone not looking to get too involved.For a quick overview here are the numbers:There are about 15 different weapon types you can choose from.There are currently 100 or so skills you can choose to specialize in.There are around 1,000 recipes to choose from when crafting.There are 60,000 levels for each skill.Level 500 Mining took me about 1 week of gametime to reach, but each higher level takes more and more time.Simple crafting recipes require about 4 different ingredients to create.Advanced crafting recipes require about 20 different ingredients.There are 52 types of harvestable nodes in the game (ores, wood, plants...)Each harvestable resource can be further broken down or combined with other resources to create even more complex components.Quick Tips:There are no levels in this game besides your levels in each skill.  Someone can have 6000 points in Fishing, but have 0 in Combat.Monsters become easier/harder to kill depending on your weapon type and your armor type.To get ""better"" weapons and armor, you must add Fittings to them to add stats.Weapons and Armor have almost no stats besides Physical Resistance without Fittings.The world is mostly player-owned apart from the starting cities.The economy is 80% player-run and 20% vendors and NPCs.The world is large.  It takes a very long time to traverse the landscape on foot, which is made easier with vehicles."
76561198011188297,Recommended,322300,13890367,"Posted: 7 January, 2015",all,That_Imperial_Officer,"I highly recomend this game for players at full release.Currently, it is in early access, and I only recomend it to those who want to bug test, activly give feedback to the developers, and tolerate a game with immense bug and glitch issues. Never buy an early access game unless that is what you are intending. Early access is not typicly for people who want to simply play a game, or people who want to test to see if they will enjoy it later. People who do this usually get a poor first impression and do not enjoy the full game, when they would have loved it at release had they not been turned off by their early access experience.Now for my actual review:This game is making huge strides at recreating the Star Wars Galaxies Pre-NGE gameplay. So much to the point that I ditched the emulator for it to participate in this games alpha/beta proccess. I can not give any comparisons to ultima online however, as I never touched that game due to personal circumstances.What this game does well is truly allow you to be what ever you want, with out a scripted story or class system get in the way. I my self love linear stories for single player expiereinces, but I never could get behind it in an MMO setting.Other things are:-Completly open world-Die hard sandbox-Caters to both PVE and PVP players without comprimisng either types play quality(VERY important to me, as I prefer PVE)-Ability to play your entire time without being a combatant, yet still fill a very important role.(Weapon Smith, Docter, Entertainer [Yes those are actually a BIG role], Resource gatherer, Cook, etc)-Ability to build your own cities (As in custom build the structures and interiors) so long as you have the people. If you get enough folk to join you, they will start to fill the NPC pop and provide quests for you-Better quest system. You get quests in the mail based on reputation. You can filter them to recieve only the quest types you want (I.E. Combat only, Resource gather only, Delivery run only)- Good Charecter customization-Excellent skill systemAnd many more features I can not rememeber at 1:35 AMThis game does have issues, but none of them are really GAME issues so much as BUG issues.Over all, I highly recomend when it comes out. Right now though, only buy if you intend on bug testing and giving feedback for the devs. I enjoy simply playing it in the proccess, but I also have an abnormaly high tolerance for masive bugs and unfinished features. If you want to enjoy minimal bugs and fully fleshed out gameplay, early access is not for you."
,Recommended,322300,16893344,"Posted: 5 July, 2015",all,iSpoon.UK,"I recently bought this on steam for £15, it truly is SWG 2.I've been really impressed with the level of customization, especially with player cities.The crafting system is complex. There is a grading system in place. 50 grade levels with F0 - A9 that applies to components, ingredients and the actual items crafted. There is a big learning curve with the crafting system and it is designed so you are dependent on other crafting professions for certain high level components.There is the normal AH, accessible from anywhere that also allows you to place work order for others to fill (think EVE).The levelling system isn't straight forward, it is similar to SWG (from what I can remember) but not exactly the same. You pick up a weapon and the beginner skills, and you level it by using the weapon. When you reach a certain level you unlock an ability, but you do not get the ability yet. There are two ways to attain the ability, one is to spend training points which are given to you for completing missions. Mission completion can also give reward you directly with a choice of ability. It's a little hard to explain.Another element of the skill/levelling system is Skill Imprinting points. All sorts of in game actions can reward you with SI points, which you can then invest in the relevant skills to give your level a boost.There are two main factions warring with each other, and you can create your own third faction and align them with either main faction. I've not had a chance to play with this feature yet but as far as I know you can change your alignment at any time.Combat seems pretty good to me but needs a little work. You can roll like in GW2 and there are a lot of combat classes such as Rifles, Automatic weapons, grenades, aerosol, bladed weapons, unarmed, blunt weapons, martial arts, axe, handguns, probably a few more and you can dual wield some of them. And shields.There are healing abilities that require a healing scanner in the main hand, so any class can heal but it requires swapping out your weapon.Anyone can play the entertainer class that dances and tells stories to give buffs. You can only do this in a ""rest"" zone, which comes in the shape of inner city bars or player placed tents when out in the wild. You can tame animals with animal handling or buy them from a genetic engineer, use robots made by robotics, go fishing, logging, foraging or mining. Place harvesters, get into hacking or diplomacy. Culinary arts can make food buffs, stims made by pharmacists. There are stylists, interior decorators, disguises, stealth, traps and quite a number more that I've not mentioned such as armour/weapons crafting etc.I know that every time a new game comes out, someone makes a huge post listing all the great features it has and tries to get people hyped. We're all a bit above that kind of hype train nonsense now but I hope that the info I've given is of some help."
76561198038946455,Recommended,322300,14941116,"Posted: 17 March, 2015",all,Pius,"over 500hrs on record, so I'm not a paid hyper.  wish I was one though...*hint hint*The game is in alpha, if you gripe about buggy stuff in betas, or full releases, stay away from this game in it's current state.  The game needs a lot of polish, and can, at times, rattle a nerve or two.  However, the game is fully playable, has a great community, great staff, and great development team.  You will almost certainly never see anything about thievery in the game.  Arguments are generally quick, and allowed to vent themselves out.  The whole atmosphere of the game is very helpful.Developers are constant presence on the forums for, both, Steam and the main site.  In-game GM's are a constant, and interactive presence.  9.5 of 10 times you need a GM for something, there is one there for you.  You whispers GM's directly for any questions, or help with bugs.  For the most part, the community will help with trying to resolve your problems before you need to speak with a GM though.  We answer the same tired questions from new people like they did for us when we were new, and nobody complains about it.Never be afraid to ask any questions in the game.  You'll always find someone to answer your question, and without belittlement.As for the actual gameplay itself:Pros -1. There's an immensely huge crafting system that will wreck your frail little minds.2. There's vehicles, and mounts.3.  There's an entire line of skills and crafting focused around taming, training, and healing pets; which can be used as mounts as they evolve.4. There's PvP.  However, atm the PvP system is a bit goofy, and arena based.  There are PvP contested areas in the world, but not currently activated for PvP combatants.  Like, you can go there, kill mobs and stuff, but can't be Pk'ed.  That will change with upcoming patches.  Also, there will be a hardcore, full Open PvP with loop drops.  This hardcore PvP server will be every definition of Hardcore.5.  You can mine, fish, gather plants, log, and set harvester machines down to do the looting for you.6.  The economy is player driven, so there is a lot of trade going on constantly.  I'm not going to lie to you though, at the game's current state, the market hotly debated upon.  There's this whole grade quality vs demand thing vs skill thing going on...  It would read to be more complicated and broken than it really is, so you'd have to experience it for yourself to understand it.7.  There are many, many different wpn choices you can choose to specialize in.8.  The world is huge, and it can take a long time to travel to some places.9.  There's player housing, both, instanced and open world.10.  There's player built and run cities.11.  There will be flight.  There was talks that once drakes are tamable, you can fly them as mounts.12.  There will be space flight, and other planets in future expansions of content.I'm sure there's a lot I'm leaving out, but I've listed a good bit.Cons -1.  Endless bugs and glitches.  (it's alpha, stuff happens)2.  The whole economy, and crafting system can be very overwhelming to new players.  At times it can still be confusing for old people.3.  Crafting needs a lot of love.  There are aspects of the crafting system that are hotly debated, and need some serious tweaking.4.  Not everything is in the game yet.  (like I said, it's alpha.)  Some things you're just going have to cope with.5.  You will get stuck a lot.  Happens to everyone, and is usually fixable with a number of in-game commands, or other tricks.6.  Things will go invisible, and you will have to exit to desktop a lot.7.   The map systems are glitchy, and at times will white-out, blackout, or brown-out; causing you to exit to desktop.8.  You're going to experience periodic server crashes.  They are not frequent, so you don't have to worry about crashing every ten minutes.9.  Questing system is glitched, and needs a lot of love.  Some quest you cannot complete, the tracking system is far from helpfu, and the rewards need a tweaking.10.  There is night and day system in the game in which NPC's are highly reliable on.  Most NPC's are out only during the day, but some are out only during the night.  This can make questing difficult, and confusing.There's a lot more I could put here, but I'm not here to scare anyone off.  The overall game-play is still very fun, very doable, and highly worth it in my opinion.  As I've repeated several times in this review, it's an Alpha game, we as a player in an Alpha Phase game, you are /will be a tester.  Testers report the bugs encountered to help improve the game.If you feel you can be patient, helpful, and want to make a difference in something, I encourage you to purchase this game and join us.  We're all friends here; even the people we dislike we get along with.  That's the type of community we have.  A good one."
