76561198024127460,Recommended,322300,18421194,"Posted: 10 October, 2015",all,hboyftw,"I will start by saying I started playing mmos back in the days of Asheron's Call. I loved it and after a while I moved on to Guild Wars and then Star Wars Galaxies. If any of you remember SWG you know that the game had a tremendous cult following in the world of mmos. WoW came out and SOE decided that their games should be pulling as much revenue as Blizzard was doing. They ended up murdering alot of what I loved about SWG though I continued to play it for a while afterwards. In the end though I just ended up going to WoW because it was a more polished game that was sticking with the vision the devs had set out for. SWG died and I played WoW for years... buying expansions as they came out. If anyone keeps up with WoW you know that it has lost half of its player base with the recent expansion not delivering on the hype of the previous xpacs. I again stuck around and gave the game a chance hoping it would pick back the pace but it just did not happen for me. So I went on a binge of trying different mmos until my buddy told me about this gem. I have to say that the game has alot of potential. Giving that we are still in alpha and how fun the game is I am very excited to see what the game will play like when it goes live.Pros:Sandbox Gameplay... This is where the game shines. Many mmos that claim to be sandbox are usually all hype and not enough substance. This game delivers at being very open ended. Even the quests are randomised and tailored to your character and the skills and approach you take.So many skills... Again I love this. There are no combat levels. Just your many skills you start off with and the choice is yours on what you want to level. If you want to be a melee then choose your weapon. The more you use it the more skill you will aquire with that weapon type. This is reflected in the crafting and non-combat skills too.The Crafting... OMG! If you like crafting in mmos and love complex and in depth systems such as SWG or the higher end minecraft mods... you will love the crafting in this game. There is so much to it you have to check it out to believe it.Other non-combat skills... Dancing, story telling, diplomacy... There are many things to do outside of combat. They claim that you can play the whole game without fighting. While I guess that is possible... I don't know if it is as feasable as they say but even still there are a slew of things to do outside of combat and crafting.Nation Building... While many games have guilds or clans that you can join this game takes a different approach and lets you create your own faction outside the two set ones called Nations. Nations are similiar to guilds except in a nation everyone outside your nation can attack you. You can form alliance with other nations to counter this but this takes building relations with other people which I find to be intriguing. The town building is very nice too and throwback again to SWG and older mmos where you can have your own housing and utility buildings for various things like shops and guildhalls.Pvp... While I haven't been able to explore alot into this yet I will say the vision of what is possible seems pretty cool. Being able to seige other player cities is the biggest addition and the devs are still implementing new systems to this. Again unlike WoW where you have just horde and alliance... this game allows you to build your own faction and thus making you a primary target for everyone. While there are ways around this it still brings alot of potential to pvp players who love open world type pvp.Animal Taming and Robots... The pet system on this game is good. The more your robotics or animal handling skill is... the more pets you can control at the price of a debuff. There are many features as well not seen in many mmos such as having to care and feed for your pets among other things.Graphical style... While alot of people shy away from the stylized graphics of this game I personally find them very suitable to the immersion. It does feel like mass effect and SWG met up and had a baby but that is perfectly fine with me since I loved both games.Free to play: and the devs swear that it won't be pay to win. We appreciate this.Cons:Stability: This is the main issue with the game right now. There is lag and crashes and just overall weird glitches rampant as of 10/10/2015. The next patch is suppose to clean alot of this out so I won't be too harsh on this. That being said this is the worst experience of the game at this stage.No instances: while this is a good thing too... I tend to find the lack of dungeon-crawling aside from the occasional cave or what-not. Just yea the pve could use a bit of a boost and not saying that instance dungeons are the way to go but in my experience this is where pve shines in mmos so the devs will just have to get creative on this aspect if they want the end game to keep those raiders hooked to this title.Crafting and other systems can be a bit overwhelming at times: Again this is both a positive and negative. I personally love the deep systems but alot of players will look at it and be like yea !@$! this. If you are familiar with crafting systems in WoW and other mmos this is by far much more sophisticated. If the devs give this kind of love to the other systems... i.e. pvp and pve that will be needed to keep a strong and dedicated player base going then yes this will be a fabulous mold of a different approach to all things mmo.So again this game is still in alpha so I am curious as to see what the devs have in store for future patches. If you are looking for a great mmo to get in on the early stages then look no further."
