76561198021345592,Not Recommended,322300,16279806,"Posted: 9 June, 2015",all,Eachna,"I'm somewhere between neutral and dislike on this game. It has it's fun elements, but the devs don't appear to understand what a sandbox game actually represents. While the game nominally supports multiple play styles, in practice the devs design the systems to force players into a very limited set of choices. It's not really a sandbox, it's an open world game with a permanently broken crafting system and a lot of missions.The more systems you have in a game, the more choices you should feel like you have. Instead, in Repop, so many of the systems they added are gated behind strict controls that it limits choice. The dev team has a few inflexible ideas on how the game ""should"" be played and they don't seem trust their future player base, so players end up with only a few inflexible options.One of the biggest draws of the old-school sandbox games Repop is supposed to be emulating is that the players were allowed a lot of latitude in what they did. That latitude is not here.A lot of fuss is made over the crafting system. Crafting has a lot of pieces and an obtuse interface, so it's easy to mistake it for a deep and interesting system. It's _confusing_, but it's not at all deep. After figuring it out, it becomes clear that it's messy and shallow and requires very little thought. Given the same pile of ingredients, a ""smart"" player and a ""stupid"" player will make exactly the same items. I would much prefer a system that allowed for intelligent decision-making on the part of the players.The materials chain has been designed so that all but one-fifth to two-fifths of the in-game production is useless. Most resources are useless. Most items you can create are useless. Despite designing the harvesting and crafting this way there's no system to constructively absorb all the useless cruft.The economy is only partially player-driven. Having figured out fairly early in the process that they were too ambitious with the crafting system, the devs integrated inexpensive vendors and common loot drops of key items that are too complex or too boring to be supplied entirely by players. Have fun slaving away clicking thousands of times to skill up making circuit boards or copper wires that can be looted off any NPC human opponent, just so you can be a provider of the high-quality versions.Lore and back story is frankly...stupid. Even the most loyal players make fun of the lore on the forums. Not surprisingly, the lore is never discussed in interviews other than to say it's an original universe.At the time I'm writing this combat is very uneven, but it has gone through a few balance passes and there's always hope they'll get something better. Right now it's almost as bad a joke as the lore.The systems have been pulled from older popular MMO's with very little thought of how they fit together. Like Star Wars Galaxies? You'll find creature handlers, imagine designers, and entertainers. The skill system has been lifted from Ultima Online. The siege system was borrowed from somewhere else. Endless re-cloning and some of the market mechanics come from Eve Online. Because the dev team is trying to recreate so many different games at once but have skipped the planning stage where they consider how the different systems inform the world, nothing fits together. It's just like the crafting..a lot of overly complicated or broken systems shimmed together with vendors and patches.If you're wiling to ride their rails, the game can be fun. If you want an old-school sandbox experience, I would look elsewhere."
76561197960626849,Not Recommended,322300,29258004,Posted: 14 January,all,SharT Magician,"DO NOT BUYThe Repopulation WAS a sci fi sandbox mmo, trying to be a resemblance of the great game Star Wars Galaxies.  The devs were fans of SWG and listened to the community and were going to make a great game that pleased fans of the sandbox mmo genre.  The game showed some promise, even though it was in some early stages of development.Then the drama happened.First the servers came down in December of 2015.  The developers claimed that the engine they used was tied to the servers the game was on, and Idea Fabrik, the company that ran them was having problems, so they needed to switch to unreal engine and that would take a while and we needed to wait.  In the mean time we all got a free survival game that was somehow going to help Repopulation come out sooner.  No big deal right?WRONG.As of January 2017 we got an update and it makes no sense considering the above facts.Repopulation was originally done in Hero engine with servers provided by Hero Cloud which was all apart of the company Idea Fabrik.Idea Fabrik has now purchased the Repopulation from the old devlopers and is putting it back on Hero engine, on Hero Cloud.IT LITERALLY MAKES NO SENSE.So we couldn't play the game we paid for, for over a year because Idea Fabrik was having problems, yet here we are getting Idea Fabrik as the new devs and going back to the old engine and servers?The same old engine that the devs said we needed to move away from?Basically this game is doomed, the old devlopers at least showed a love for this game/genre and really wanted to make something great.  The new team can't possibly have that same passion they had and if the old developers were right about the importance of switching to unreal engine, we are probably stuck with a bad engine.I do not blame the new developers taking over and will gladly give them a shot when the servers come up in Q1 2017.  But a lot of us are not happy with how the old team handled this game and the future is looking pretty grim for it.  But, I will gladly rewrite this review when the new team gets everything together, but even then, I don't have high expectations.EDIT:If you have an issue with the reveiw leave comments instead of just downvoting so I can address the issue.Otherwise it seems like fanboys ignoring facts."
