,Recommended,322300,13897449,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,Dachartach,"I'm certainly not very far into it, but so far it looks promising. It's a skill based advancement system, where you obtain skill points through missions or by using the skills. New skills are available by buying the books from NPCs. The crafting system looks ""deep,"" which means complicated; but, much like in SWG(you're going to see that a lot), this is not needlessly so. Most gear will be crafted by other players, and the key elements for modifying stats are fittings, which are modular modifications that you put into your armor or weapons. The tutorial is raw, and consists of popping up a database page describing what to do. Read these. Once you finisht the tutorial you will have several skills and pieces of equipment for your future endeavors.I have not gotten into too much of the main story missions, and I think you may need to build up some reputation before you get access to the lore. You do get missions in your mailbox regularly, and it is made clear in the tutorial that you don't have to do them all. Once I entered Freedomtown I received 4 messages with missions very quickly.Graphics are alright for this level of development, of course they will be expected to improve after what is an Alpha.5 build. My biggest problem is that the client keeps crashing to desktop, and apparently this is an issue for many other players. It is not totally unexpected, but I WANT TO PLAY. WAH.All that aside, I am looking forward to getting into the gathering and crafting. Finding some materials was not as difficult as in SWG, and once you find a node you have the option to enhance the node or the area to improve the quality of the materials you take. Also, various quality materials stack, so you can have F0 all the way up to A10 quality of a commodity all in one stack. Oh yes, you can break them up later. So yes, I think this will be a good one, all the proper elements are in place. Sometimes you just have to sack up, roll a hard 6, show up and see what happens. This should be pretty good."
