76561198094401432,Not Recommended,322300,13904684,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,Dodece,"Potential is a poor justification, and an even poorer measure. You need to review what is present, and not what it may, or in fact may not become. This is a sandbox game that isn't quite delivering on the promise of open world freedom. The reality is that beneath the veneer of choice. Is a virtual lack thereof. In a lot of ways it is the worst of two worlds. Either the game demands an obscene amount of interdependency to get anything done, or its so simplistic a cave man can do it. If you will pardon the pun.I am torn as to whether the combat is laughable or awful. The game supports two combat styles first person mode, or the standard hot button mode. The problem with the first is that while it makes it easier to navigate it makes combat pretty easy as it make decissions for you. The problem with the second is while it is somewhat more challenging it is also more of a pain to use to navigate. Not that it matters either way virtually no strategy or movement is required. Either you are going to dominate or you are going to die.The loot system is perhaps the worst I have ever seen, and it has nothing to do with the odds involved with random rolls. This game makes use of a slot machine that can take between thirty or forty seconds to finish its roll. Just to give you a random loot that probably wont apply. In other words you will not only have to wait for loot, but it wont even be close to being something you might be able to use.  What you end up doing is spinning for quality of you know not what, at least if you knew. Then you could decide in advance to abandon the roll, and abandon the corpse.The reason for this awful loot system is the horribly convoluted crafting system. That is predicated on a slavish devotion to a perverse notion of interdependency. Crafters are relegated to nothing more then cogs in a machine. Everyone can craft, but nobody can make something on their own. There are at least half a dozen harvesting lines in the game, and it is a foregone conlusion that if a schematic requires three ingredients that all three ingredients will require different kinds of harvesting, and at least one, and possibly two will require an intermediate refining before they can be used, and all of that is the case if you are lucky. You might be unlucky, and one of the ingredients might be a crafted component that has to be purchased from another player, and well if one isn't up for sale wow it really sucks to be you.Worse still for the crafter, and the resultant buyer the quality of ingredients matters, and they are the product of random rolls. So as it stands the real question should be why have the crafting system at all. Is the crafter supposed to wait for an accomplished harvester to get a few good rolls, and what of the other crafter, and what if their rolls don't pan out. It is a recipe for conniption fits if I saw one.Beyond all of that however. The user interfase is pretty abysmal. I mean basic functionality isn't even there.  I hope that is temp music we are hearing, and that they intend for it to be instance appropriate, and the graphics are pretty bad in a lot of ways. It is one thing for the world to be muddy, but the animals are too, and seeing as how everything is hostile it is a pretty big problem.Potential or not there are some pretty bad design philosophies present in this build, and while I would love to play a real successor to star wars galaxies. Which is what this developer is going after. What made that game fun wasn't so much its complexities as much as it was the sense of freedom, and this game doesn't seem to be promoting freedom of choice. It is forcing crafters to network, boring combat players with idiotic looting systems, and the combat isn't very involved. It could get better, but then again it could get worse, and I am concerned it will be the latter.It is a sad fact of life that a number of sandbox players just don't have any life to speak of, and they often operate under the delusion that theirs is a common playstyle. A lot of the testers don't appear to be making allowances for this, and are likely to encourage the developer to keep the system as is, because it favors their style of play while punishing the player that has a life outside of the game.I can't really recommend this game at this time. There is a lot of mindless grinding, but not much else to recommend it. It  is so hard in some regards, and so terribly easy in others. That it is a hard place to have much fun. You shouldn't pay much attention to the positive reviews. Most of them are coming from ex star wars galaxies players who are going on a decade thirsty for a proper title in the genre. It is to be expected that they would be far more forgiving, and frankly far easier to give themselves over to self delusion.That all said there is hope in the developer. As they seem to be very responsive, and they seem to be very attentive. It is usually a good sign when the developers are listening closely.  Which is why I intend to revisit the game periodically to see if it is improving. If it manages to do that I will probably amend this review."
